Get Read Counts

1. We would like to know the count of reads that overlap each target region for each sample. Use a command line tool or notebook / script to create a file containing a matrix of the read counts where the columns are the target regions and the rows are the read counts.

Your answer should look approximately like the file provided in example_results/counts.tsv (exact answers may vary due to subtle issues of how read overlaps or boundaries are considered - do not worry about this). 

# mode = "Union" : (Default) Reads that overlap any portion of exactly one feature are counted. 
#                  Reads that overlap multiple features are discarded. 
#                  This is the most conservative of the 3 modes.
# fragments = FALSE: (Default FALSE) A logical; applied to paired-end data only.
#                    fragments controls which function is used to read the data which subsequently 
#                    affects which records are included in counting.
#                    When fragments=FALSE, data are read with readGAlignmentPairs and returned 
#                    in a GAlignmentPairs class. 
#                    In this case, singletons, reads with unmapped pairs, and other fragments, are dropped.
se <- summarizeOverlaps(features = gr, reads = bamfiles,
                        mode = "Union", singleEnd = FALSE,
                        ignore.strand = TRUE, fragments = FALSE)
tmp1 <- t(assay(se))
colnames(tmp1) <- paste(as.character(seqnames(gr)), paste(start(gr), end(gr), sep = '-'), sep = ':')
tmp2 <-  as.matrix(x = gsub('.bam', '', rownames(tmp1)), ncol = 1)
colnames(tmp2) <- 'sample'
data <- cbind(as.data.table(tmp2), as.data.table(tmp1))
data[1:2, 1:4]
##    sample chrX:31119228-31121932 chrX:31126642-31126675 chrX:31134102-31134196
## 1:  XI001                     34                     20                     37
## 2:  XI002                     48                     39                     44
write.table(x = data, file = 'results/counts.tsv', append = FALSE, 
            quote = FALSE, sep = '\t', row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE)


2. Use your preferred data analysis language to normalise each sample by dividing out its mean coverage - save this file as results/mean.counts.tsv 

dat <- data[, grep('chr', names(data), value = TRUE), with = FALSE]
res <- data.table(sample = data$sample, mean_coverage = rowMeans(dat))
res[1:2,]
##    sample mean_coverage
## 1:  XI001      29.35443
## 2:  XI002      41.44304
write.table(x = res, file = 'results/mean.counts.tsv', append = FALSE, 
            quote = FALSE, sep = '\t', row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE)

Intepret PCA

4. Describe what you see in the PCA plot. Can you interpret anything from the data?

The PCA plot above shows that:

  • The first principal component (PC1) explains 41.4% variation of read counts in the dataset (x-axis).
  • The second principal component (PC2) explains 8.7% variation of read counts in the dataset (y-axis).
  • Individual 4 has a read count profile most different from other individuals, shown as the largest dot size in red colour furtherest away from the centre of the coordinates.
  • Individual 5 has a read count profile second the most different from other individuals, shown as the second largest dot size in orange colour also further away from the centre of the coordinates.

The eigenvalues for each PC are listed below.

  • The first 2 PCs explain 50% of variation of read counts.
  • The first 5 PCs explain 70% variation of read counts.

Special Samples

5. Based on your findings, are there any particular samples you would recommend to treat specially or differently in this data?

To identify whether or not there are outliers in the dataset, the target region with the most varied read counts was selected.
An Grubbss test was performed to detect whether or not there are outliers in the most varied target region.
No outlier was identified, indicating that no sample or target region needs to be removed due to potential technical errors.

plvl <- 0.01
res.desc <- dimdesc(res.pca, axes = 1, proba = plvl)
cns <- rownames(res.desc$Dim.1[[1]])[1]
x <- array(dat[, cns, with = F])[[1]]
grubbs.test(x)
## 
##  Grubbs test for one outlier
## 
## data:  x
## G = 1.77731, U = 0.73832, p-value = 0.4306
## alternative hypothesis: lowest value 25 is an outlier

The vector below shows that:

  • Individual 2 and 5 have the same read count in target region chrX:31679375-31679588.
  • Individual 2 and 5 have the largest read count among all individuals.
  • Read counts of individual 2 and 5 are 1.35 times more than the mean read count of other individuals.
x <- dat$"chrX:31679375-31679588"
dt <- x / mean(x)
dt
##  [1] 0.5709625 1.3474715 1.1419250 0.7536705 1.3474715 1.0734095 1.0277325
##  [8] 1.1876020 0.7765090 0.7079935 1.2104405 0.9135400 0.8678630 1.0734095


The Q-Q plot below shows that individuals read counts in this target region are fairly normally distributed, as most dots falling on the diagonal straight line.

qqnorm(x)
qqline(x)


A one-sample t-test was performed to compare read counts of individual 2 and 5 with that of other individuals.
The test examines whether or not the mean read counts of other individuals fewer than the read count of individual 2 and 5 is statistically significant, but the test does not examine whether or not the difference in read counts is sufficient to suggest a heterozyous duplication in individual 2 and 5.
Results show that individual 2 and 5 have read counts statistically significantly larger than other individuals in the target region.
There are 79 target regions.
Multiple testings occur when a one-sample t-test is performed for each target region.
Given a p-value threshold of 0.01, after Bonferroni correction, the test p-value remains significant, indicating that individual 2 and 5 may have a copy number duplication in the target region chrX:31679375-31679588.
This target region falls within an exon of the Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) gene, where copy number duplication is a known mechanism of diseases (Decipher and GnomAD).
Whether this candidate copy number duplication is relevant to disease or not will depend on the clinical presentations of individaul 2 and 5.

ttest <- t.test(x = x[c(1, 3:4, 6:14)], mu = x[5], alternative = 'less')
ttest

## data:  x[c(1, 3:4, 6:14)]

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 45.97116
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     41.25
ttest$p.value < 0.01/ncol(dat)

A one-sample t-test was performed to compare read counts of individual 4 with that of other individuals.
The test examines whether or not the mean read counts of other individuals larger than the read count of individual 4 is statistically significant, but the test does not examine whether or not the difference in read counts is sufficient to suggest a heterozyous deletion in individual 4.
Results show that individual 4 has read counts statistically significantly fewer than other individuals in the target region.
There are 79 target regions.
Multiple testings occur when a one-sample t-test is performed for each target region.
Given a p-value threshold of 0.01, after Bonferroni correction, the test p-value remains significant, indicating that there could be a copy number deletion in the target region.
This target region falls within an exon of the Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) gene, where copy number deletion is a known mechanism of diseases (Decipher and GnomAD).
Whether or not this candidate copy number deletion is relevant to disease will depend on the clinical presentation of individaul 4.

The test examines whether or not the mean read counts of other individuals fewer than the read count of individual 5 is statistically significant, but the test does not examine whether or not the difference in read counts is sufficient to suggest a heterozyous duplication in individual 5.
Results show that individual 5 has read counts statistically significantly larger than rest of the individuals in the target region.
